Part One:<br>
The Betrayal<br>
<br>
        He sneaked into Greater Faydark unnoticed. A part of a contingency of guards sent to escort the Dark Elf Ambassador to the settlement of orcs on the northern border of that realm. The human shadowknight knew that he and his fellow humans were tools. They were being used by the Teir’Dal, but most of them were too young and bloodthirsty to know or care. He was different. He knew that once this “Dvinn” was installed in his position that the human escort was going to be slaughtered. They would most likely be fed to the pathetic pawns as a living goodwill gesture. <br>
<br>
        As they ran underneath the tree city of Kelethin, the knight of the dark chuckled to himself at the irony of the moment. All of us running beneath the city of druids and rangers. They claim to be so attuned to nature and yet we march directly under their noses. The fools.<br>
<br>
        At last the torches of Emperor Crush’s home came into view. The shadowknight bowed to the Ambassador and saluted the centurion that came out to greet them. “We will be returning to Freeport now.” He said to the two.<br>
<br>
        “But wait.” Dvinn bid them stay. “The other half of your payment is in the Emperor’s hands. He wishes to give you all your reward personally.” The sick, corrupt smile that slid across the Teir’Dal face almost turned the knights stomach. Had he not spent all of those tours based at the Kunark outpost hunting the abominations, the Sarnak, he might have been intimidated.<br>
<br>
        His mentor, the fallen avatar Sir Lucan, had warned the knight just before his first mission with the Dark Elves. He said, “Be wary of the Teir’Dal. Their evil is not like ours. We chose our paths with consciousness and conviction. Their evil is just not natural Their minds have been twisted more than they know by the Dark Lord, Innoruuk. They will use you until they use you up. Then they will throw you out.”<br>
<br>
        The evil elf sensed his reluctance and slithered over to his side, wrapping an arm around his shoulder as he led the men into the orc domain. “Come, Captain. We must not show any disrespect to the good Emperor. We wish to aid them in their struggle against the accursed tree-huggers.” A smile full of mirth crossed his thin blue lips then, a smile that never touched the man’s eyes.<br>
<br>
        Through the Crushbone encampment the humans were led. The knight glanced worriedly around him, finding nothing but the ugly, sneering faces of the wretched orcs. When at last they came upon the castle, there were several much larger orcs waiting for them.<br>
<br>
        Dvinn released the Captain and stepped towards the line of the orc leaders. He made a slow bow and the orcs raised themselves up in self-importance and arrogance. The Captain could see the contempt in the bow though. He knew this creature for what he truly was.<br>
<br>
        “Welcome, Dark Elf.” The orc at the center of the line began. He was somewhat shorter than the other monstrosities, but more solidly built. That must be Emperor Crush. “I trust you come in good faith?” He smiled around his yellowed fangs.<br>
<br>
        Dvinn turned to face the humans gracefully with a malicious gleam in his eyes. He began to walk around them, “Of course. We of the Indigo Brotherhood always show our goodwill.”<br>
<br>
        This set alarms off in the shadowknight’s head. He quickly began summoning his energies as he watched the orcs immediately leap in on the unsuspecting humans. They were being beaten, dragged off still screaming and praying to the Dark Lord for deliverance. He had to get away. His shadow began to elongate, and he wondered where the Ambassador was. Just as he stepped into the shadow, he felt a blade slip into his back. The pain seared in his mind, but he focused harder on his spell. He had to get away! The last thing he heard was the Ambassador gloating, “Hardly a worthy opponent.”<br>
<br>
        The shadows closed in around him and dropped him somewhere else in the camp. He was always a little disoriented after using that. This time it almost dropped him off of a cliff. He backed away from the edge, just out of sight of the hut near the bottom of the precipice, with a murky pond between the two. He dropped to the ground, bleeding badly from the knife wound in his back. The shadows of his eyelids closed in on him as his consciousness slipped away.<br>
<br>
The Story of Uhrlik<br>
Part Two:<br>
Chance Encounters<br>
<br>
<br>
        As the shadows parted the pain returned. The Captain had not expected to wake up again. He realized that he was on his side, but he had been laying on his stomach. There was a hand on his arm as well. He started to sit up, and the hand pressed down firmly but gently. The skin was soft and warm.<br>
<br>
        He maneuvered his arm free to scrub out his eyes. He discovered that his chest was bandaged tightly and the blood had stopped. He felt a warm energy rush into him and his wounds began to close on their own. <br>
<br>
        The shadowknight lifted his head to gaze into the eyes of a vision. Her auburn hair fell across graceful features, and her dark, almond shaped eyes peered into him with a strange mixture of concern and trepidation. The whole of her being seemed composed of beauty and serenity. The sun glared down so that she appeared to be wearing a halo of pure light almost as peaceful and stunning as she was.<br>
<br>
        He felt his eyes widen and he blushed. She chuckled lightly. The Captain had never imagined that a servant of Innoruuk could become enamored so quickly.<br>
<br>
        “I am called Uhrsalla Puresoul,” She smiled warmly at him.<br>
<br>
        He began sitting up slowly, felling much better as time went by. “My name is Amlik Shadowblade.” He fingered the wrappings around his chest, “I thank you for your kindness, but I am afraid that I cannot return the favor. You are a wood elf and I should most likely kill you.”<br>
<br>
        Uhrsalla shrugged, “Then I will meet the Mother of All with a clear conscience.” She studiously ignored the symbol of the Dark Lord dangling from his neck. <br>
<br>
        “How did you find me? It’s very dangerous here.” Amlik questioned.<br>
<br>
        “We came to free some of our captured countrymen. Some of them are lucky to be eaten.” She seemed on the verge of tears as if remembering a pain very close to home, a pain that would never heal.<br>
<br>
        This had been the first that Amlik had noticed the familiar sounds of battle going on around him. The races of Faydwer, the high elves, wood elves and dwarves were raiding the encampment and taking back their fellows. The companionship of the nations astounded him.<br>
<br>
The shadowknight laid a hand on his savior’s shoulder. “You do not have to tell me, but I wish to help you…” He clipped the sentence short as the word “forever” nearly escaped his lips. <br>
<br>
He grunted as Uhrsalla hugged him tightly, but oddly, it felt good. This was what he was meant for.<br>
<br>
The Story of Uhrlik<br>
Part Three:<br>
A new star in the sky<br>
<br>
<br>
        Amlik and Uhrsalla spent every moment together. The orcs in the slaver camp were never a match for either of them, but Amlik refused to venture any deeper. He told her about Dvinn, of course, but he had not told her that he wanted Dvinn to think that he had died. He was saving his strength for a time when he could exact his revenge on the treacherous Dark Elf. The hatred seethed in him, growing alongside his love for his druid savior. He pushed the hatred down though, muted it enough to marry Uhrsalla.<br>
<br>
        It was a joyous ceremony, marked with gnomish fireworks and far too much liquor. Still Amlik could not rid himself of that hate, could not allow the peace that emanated from his wife to soak into him completely.<br>
<br>
        Amlik had been sent to check on the camp of Master Wu, where reports said he had been driven off or killed by invading Teir’Dal. Their incursion worried him. It was almost like the Dark Elves were surrounding the Elven cities to catch them unaware. Sure there was the Estate of Mayong Mistmoore there, but Mistmoore’s Teir’Dal hated even their dark cousins. They were largely contained. The brownies helped make sure of that. They made travel through Lesser Faydark extremely dangerous.<br>
<br>
        He returned home to Kelethin to find his wife surrounded by several well-aged and respected druids. The women all had a somber look on their faces as they all turned to face him. His wife beamed a smile at him regardless of their reactions. He could feel the warmth in her heart radiate out to him as she lay a hand on her abdomen.<br>
<br>
        “You’re going to…” He couldn’t speak. She merely nodded. As they embraced, tears welled up in Amlik’s eyes. He was going to be a father.<br>
<br>
        Time disappeared and the pregnancy went well. Uhrsalla had never looked more beautiful to him. Soon, they had a new baby. A new baby boy.<br>
<br>
        “We’ll call him Uhrlik,” Uhrsalla panted and glowed while holding their new baby in her arms.<br>
<br>
        “It’s a fine name. And he has much of you in him. So when he’s old enough, he will take our combined surname, Pureblade.”<br>
<br>
        Amlik prayed to no one in particular for his son to have his mother’s nobility and spirit. He hoped that his son would be spared the unrelenting hate that poisoned his own heart. The once shadowknight of Innoruuk was a father now. It was difficult to adjust to that.<br>
<br>
<br>
