The Story of Uhrlik<br>
Part Four:<br>
Night falls<br>
<br>
Several years passed and Uhrlik was developing well. Amlik showed him how to handle a sword, which he loved. He walked around with his small practice sword everywhere he went. He slay imaginary dragons on the way to the breakfast table in the morning, and defeated hordes of orcs alone on his way to bed at night.<br>
<br>
They could not get him to attempt magic, though. The boy should have had natural magical powers, but he refused to tap into them. Try as they might, he could not be moved. Another quality he had garnered from his mother, Amlik noted flatly.<br>
<br>
Since the boy was of mixed parentage, he found that some of the other children shied away from him. He became very introverted. Watching their son walking away from a group of children his own age because they didn’t want to play with a “half-breed” broke Uhrsalla’s heart. Amlik watched the boy clutch the sword in his little hands so tight that his knuckles turned white. He watched young Uhrlik mouth the words, “You are my real friend. You won’t desert me.” There was a strange sense of pride in that for the erstwhile shadowknight.<br>
<br>
So the boy spent his first years alone. He spent his days hunting in the woods, careful to avoid the orcs, and at night he cried while his mother sang him to sleep. One such night, Uhrsalla could take no more.<br>
<br>
“We should move away from here. Go somewhere Uhrlik will be accepted.” She whispered.<br>
<br>
Amlik considered the idea briefly, but could not think of anyplace that would be any more accepting than Kelethin. He told her so, adding, “Once he makes a name for himself, they will love him as a true Feir’Dal. You have done well with him, Heart, he is a true Good Elf.”<br>
<br>
“We have done well with him,” she corrected him as she curled up beside him.<br>
<br>
The subject was closed for that night, but it was far from forgotten. Amlik had seen much of the world in the service of the Teir’Dal. He knew that the half-elves of the world were wanderers at best. They had no society and the only way they could be accepted was to fight. They had to earn everything they got. It saddened him that he had subjected a noble spirit such as Uhrlik to this fate, but he believed that if anyone could overcome these obstacles it would be his boy. There was still that growing sense of loneliness in him though. That emptiness would be his biggest challenge, Amlik feared.<br>
<br>
The youth continued training on his own, making his best attempts to convince his parents that he was fine, that he enjoyed the solitude. He put up quite a show. Every once in a while, Amlik came around a corner just in time to see Uhrlik selling orcish weapons and armor. A mix of emotions filled him. There was pride, surely, but worry as well. He was sure that he wore the same expression now that his love had worn when she had tended his wounds so long ago.<br>
<br>
He planned on telling Uhrsalla that night as they sat down to eat dinner. Fate, it seemed, had a different plan. Explosions broke the song of the night birds, shouts from the guard outposts.<br>
<br>
“Orcs invading, to arms!” One of the ground guards shouted.<br>
<br>
Amlik rushed out the door, grabbing his sword on his way out. Uhrsalla and Uhrlik ran out behind him. The once shadowknight scanned the horizon. His eyes were no good at night. What he could see chilled him to the bone. These orcs were too organized. Their movements were too precise. This was Dvinn’s work.<br>
<br>
“You two stay here.” He ordered and stalked off. He knew that they would not obey, but he had to try.<br>
<br>
Leaping from the platform, Amlik tried to get a better fix on the enemy movements. There seemed to be nothing gained from this. Any orc that came within arm’s reach of a guard died quickly, without exception. Then it came to him. A small detachment of Legionnaires and four oracles were heading toward the massive tree trunks that held up the Tree City.<br>
<br>
At once the legionnaires turned on him. The oracles began moving into position, preparing to burn their way through the gigantic support. The orc warriors were no match for his steel, and they died quickly. Amlik rushed to find the oracles. He could hear the guards shouting for reinforcements. They had to do something to stem the tide of the misshapen beasts. Guards came leaping from their posts on top of the city, cleaving orcs as they hit the ground.<br>
<br>
Atop the city, he could see Uhrsalla’s hands burning and she pointed. Wherever her flaming hands pointed a massive explosion ripped the ground and anything else apart. Her druid sisters and brothers joined her, healing the rangers as they darted from orc to orc. The ranger blades flashed quickly and orcs died wherever they met.<br>
<br>
The blue skinned monstrosities did not stop. They kept coming like a terrible ocean. Wave after wave, all stronger and better armed than the last. It appeared that the city might not survive the night.<br>
<br>
Amlik ducked past a throng of guards slaughtering the invaders and found his quarry. The four oracles were chanting. He had caught them in the middle of casting. Reaching down as he ran, he picked up a shield and charged into them. As Amlik collided with them, the flame around their hands died. They prepared to unleash their fury on him, but he struck them down swiftly. The once shadowknight stopped for a moment, panting.<br>
<br>
Something familiar pricked the back of his mind, and his neck hairs stood up on end. Turning, an explosion illuminated the form of his nemesis: Dvinn. The slick Teir’Dal flashed his teeth at Amlik in a mock smile. The hate that had been seething inside him instantly surfaced and he rushed the Ambassador with a snarl. Dvinn merely twirled a strange black-bladed dagger in his hand and waved him on.<br>
<br>
The Dark Elf parried the massive sword with ease, laughing the whole time. Amlik backed off to regroup and the sinister Ambassador nodded to him, saluted, and disappeared. The knight turned in circles looking for his dangerous prey. Things were going badly for the wood elves. The druids were running out of power to heal. Their energies were depleted. The warriors and rangers were doing their best to fight by the sides of the guards, but more seemed to be dropping every minute. The fatigue of war was setting in.<br>
<br>
Just then, Amlik felt the hair on his neck standing up again and he dodged to the side. From the corner of his eye, he saw the black bladed dagger darting past him, gleaming wetly in the firelight. He slashed to where the man had been, but found nothing there. Time after time, the twisted elf tried to pierce Amlik but found his enemy just out of reach.<br>
<br>
Anger seethed in the Teir’Dal’s blood. He became visible again, having lost his concentration. The two blades met again in a fury of blows. The hatred between the two grew until it was nearly tangible in the surrounding air.<br>
<br>
The Ambassador parried once more and hit Amlik alongside his head with the pommel of the dagger, stunning him. Dvinn laughed a maniacal laugh as he plunged the dagger into Amlik’s stomach. The poison burned into the shadowknight’s veins as he sank to his knees.<br>
<br>
“The Indigo Brotherhood always gets its way.” He laughed and turned away.<br>
<br>
“D…Dvinn…” Amlik spat weakly. The poison was working quickly. The Dark Elf turned around with a smug satisfaction on his face. “Y…You won’t get away…with this…”<br>
<br>
“But I will, and we both know it.”<br>
<br>
The shadowknight thought about his wife and son, thought about them falling into the hands of this monster, or into the cook pots like his men all those years ago. Their gnawed and meatless bones still littered the ground of Crush’s home. The desperation and hatred boiled over in him and he reached out once more to the power of the Dark Lord, Innoruuk.<br>
<br>
“You may have killed me, rogue, but my son will have my revenge. I curse you!” Striking out with all of the hate of his life he grabbed the man, draining the Ambassador in a flash of green smoke, crippling him. “You will never pose a threat again. Your fearsome powers will now only scare children. And one day, my son will find you and kill you.”<br>
<br>
Dvinn shook and sweated profusely. His power had indeed been stolen. But this man could not contain his power for long, or could he? There was no flow. He had truly been crippled. Realization of his weakness shot across his face and he retreated back to the safety of Crush’s tower.<br>
<br>
The dying knight clutched his wound tightly and convulsed in pain. He turned his eyes back to the battle and realized with horror the true purpose of the fight. He watched the pawns and centurions erecting tents and setting up camp. They had thrown themselves into the arms of death to gain a little ground on the wood elves. They were being driven back, now. The high elves had joined the battle with their paladins and powerful spellcasters. The clerics rushed through the battlefield healing the wounded and saying a prayer for the dead. The dwarves came with their powerful warriors and their own righteous knights. Dawn was coming in Greater Faydark, it seemed.<br>
<br>
“Father!” Uhrlik shouted over the din. His voice was ragged. He had been fighting. Amlik turned to face his son for the last time. The boy saw the wound and said one word, “Dvinn.”<br>
 <br>
Uhrsalla rushed up behind their son and dashed down to the ground, holding her love. She tried summoning her energies to cure the poison, but it was too late. She tried everything she could until she had no energy left. Then she cried. She held him tightly and prayed to Tunare to deliver him.<br>
<br>
Amlik laid a hand on hers and tried to silence her. He felt at peace then, felt the tranquility of her love. He let it wash over him as he slowly slipped into the night. He watched his son, with his arms bloody to his elbows and his little practice sword clutched tightly in his right hand. When did he grown so big? He asked himself absently. The young man turned to face the home of the orcs and his face grew severe.<br>
<br>
“One day I will kill you all. I will have revenge for my father.” Then he screamed with the anguish of the moment, “Do you hear me Dvinn? I am coming for you. Count on it.” He panted and said in a low voice, “I will destroy evil wherever I see it. This I promise to you, Father.”<br>
<br>
Amlik closed his eyes slowly, slipping into the night and he whispered “I love you…” Then Amlik Shadowblade, a dark knight of Innoruuk that became a hero to the wood elves; Amlik Pureblade, husband of Uhrsalla, father of Uhrlik, died.<br>
<br>
