The Story of Uhrlik<br>
Part Five:<br>
A Secret Revealed<br>
<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp That night, Uhrlik’s father burned on a pyre next to so many others. The night was turned to day by the light of the dead. Uhrlik could not cry that night, pushing his emotions down, turning them into a ball of driving force, his own personal hatred. <br>
<br>
His mother, Uhrsalla, sang to the dead. It was a dirge that helped them find their way back to the Mother of All. What about his father, though? He had been a follower of Innoruuk. Where would he go? Certainly not to Tunare. Despite his efforts to be a loving father and husband, his hard work to keep the Faydark safe and protect the Feir’Dal, he had still been a disciple of Hate. He knew that his mother hoped she would see him in the afterlife, but Uhrlik did not think so.<br>
<br>
The answers did not come that night, but the youth watched his father’s pyre burn until the embers had cooled and the ashes were scattered on the wind. For three days he sat at the pile of scorched timbers thinking, reviewing. <br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The orcs had taken up residence to the north of Kelethin. The Elves and Dwarves were victorious in driving them back for the moment. There was also a rumor that the gnomes had sabotaged a Teir’Dal invasion force in Lesser Faydark that would have destroyed Felwithe, home of the High Elves. The world had changed in the course of one night. Nothing could ever be the same again.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Taking up his short sword, his little practice sword, he stumbled home, exhausted and numb. He found his mother had not slept yet either, and her eyes were red and puffy from crying. He could feel her pain, feel her emptiness. She felt as if she was missing the half of herself that actually mattered to her. The boy embraced his mother, and he held her through the bone wracking sobs and fits of denial.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp It took weeks for her to stop crying, but she was never right afterwards. Uhrsalla never went outside, never sang and barely spoke. She refused to eat. Like a wolf without her mate, she was slowly withering away.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Uhrlik continued to hunt the orcs, this time with a new ferocity. He spent long hours on the newly usurped hill north of the city and went home late at night to care for his mother. She was pale and thin, and had recently developed a raspy cough that worried him. He cooked for her, a skill that he promised himself he would get better at one day, but she ate almost nothing.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Watching his mother fading slowly away fueled the new hate within the youth. He ventured farther into the orcish encampment, slaughtering all that stood before him. He spent more and more time in the wild, unable to bear watching his mother die by inches. He joined others from the city that hunted the orcs. His reputation for killing the misshapen creatures with tireless zeal was becoming well known among the hunters. But inside the hate was growing.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Soon, the young warrior was attacking Crushbone itself. He and his comrades forced their way into the quarters of the Slavers, where the ramshackle hut and the mine were littered with elves and dwarves taken prisoner in the all too common orc raids.  Rummaging through the corpse of one Slaver, Uhrlik found a key. He crept over to one of the slaves and tried the key on the poor man’s shackles. With a painfully loud CLICK the cuffs opened and the elven man was free. He spoke in hushed tones of Dvinn, warning that he had only seen the man on two or three occasions, but it was the time that he didn’t see the Ambassador that scared him. “Never turn your back on that one. And pray that you never meet him. Tunare bless you, I’m free!”<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Other slaves, once freed, mentioned that Dvinn had orchestrated the mining operation. He had ordered the training of a Taskmaster. A powerful orc that could keep the other Slavers on their toes through fear, the only force that motivated the orcs aside from greed and hunger. Some of them believed that the sinister man was looking for something. A magical item or a powerful relic that his order could twist with their foul magic.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Days passed by and Uhrlik lost count of the number of slaves he returned to their families. He went into the orcish domain at sunrise every morning and staggered home with the moon over full rise. One night he was arriving home very late. The sun was rising on the horizon, turning the sky into a blazing show of color.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The young one stumbled off of the lift and began the trek to find his home while increasingly desperate for his bed. All of the guards smiled as he walked by. The same men that had shot distasteful looks at him as a child. He was very nearly home when he slammed right into the armored chest of Captain Silverwind, the captain of the Kelethin guards. Lurching backwards, trying not to fall, he focused his eyes on the captain. Silverwind smiled and salted him with the traditional warrior salute, sword over heart. Uhrlik bowed deeply and the Captain laughed and ruffled his hair.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp At home, Uhrlik found his mother out of bed and clothed in the dress she had married his father in. The sun was shining brightly now and the birds were singing a lilting tune. His heart jumped into his throat and his stomach felt like it was full of ice.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “Mother? What are you doing?”<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Uhrsalla turned to her son with a wide smile on her face, “I can hear the Mother calling.” She cocked her head to the side, “Can you hear her song? It’s so beautiful.”<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Uhrlik strained to listen, but heard nothing. “What are you talking about, Mother?”<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp She appeared not to hear him as she lay down on her bed with her hands folded over her stomach. She eyed him for a long moment and the smile slid from her face. “You know, I worry about you.” Uhrsalla stated as she waved her son to her side.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Uhrlik dashed to the stool that he kept next to her headboard and sat down, the same stool he sat on when feeding her, he noted. “Why, Mother?”<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “I have had a glimpse of your future. It troubles me greatly. I feel I must tell you before I go.”<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “What did you see?” The boy inquired with tears in his eyes.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “I saw you knocking on the door to Innoruuk’s domain. I have felt the hate ebbing from you like a black sea these last months. Do not let the corruption that killed your father envelop you too. I will not be able to rest in peace knowing that you were following such a path to destruction.”<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “Do not say such things, Mother. You will be fine. You just need to eat.” Uhrlik grasped desperately at any sense of normalcy he could find. He stood up quickly and started towards the kitchen, but Uhrsalla stopped him with a feeble hand on his wrist.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “The Mother is calling me home. I have to go. I want to go. Do not turn your back on her. She loves you as her own child. She has told me this.”<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The young warrior sat back down slowly and lowered his head to hide the tears streaming from his eyes like rain, “I truly hope that Father is waiting on the other side for you.”<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Uhrsalla smiled and closed her eyes, “I know I will see him again. I found him once after all.”<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp And there, Uhrsalla Puresoul, faithful daughter of Tunare the Mother of All, Uhrsalla Pureblade, faithful mother of Uhrlik died.<br>
<br>
<br>
