The Story of Uhrlik<br>
Part Six:<br>
Friends in Vengeance<br>
<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Uhrlik did not wait for the embers of his mother’s pyre to cool. He snatched up his sword, his piecemeal armor and his meager belongings and locked the door to his house. He walked away without ever looking back.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp As night rolled over the Faydark, the young warrior curled up underneath the platform of his former home. The night grew cold and Uhrlik shook in the darkness, alone and empty except for the gnawing hatred that seethed in his gut.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp How could the Mother of All take his mother from him so lightly? How could he follow a goddess that could be so cavalier about death? Innoruuk was no answer either. He had taken his father away, too. There was nothing he could find in the entire pantheon of the gods to justify worship.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “My trust is in myself now,” he mumbled half asleep. “My trust is in steel.”<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Shivering through the night, Uhrlik drifted between consciousness and deep sleep. He saw himself, only different. He wore heavy plate-like armor as mismatched as his emotions. The armor nearly glowed the magic inherent in it was so strong. A flaming reddish breastplate stood out almost as much as the weapons he wielded.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp In his right hand was a massive metal haft like a spear that ended in a blade crafted in the shape of a dragon’s head. In his left was a very light and obviously well made sword, the blade flaring like a leaf at the point.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp There was a confidence and experience in the doppelganger’s eyes. He lifted his left hand and struck a massive door with the pommel of the sword. The door opened slowly and the shadows within cackled maniacally. His shadow self began to march into the door, his hate washing over the scene in bone-chilling waves. <br>
<br>
Suddenly, an army appeared at his back, as if the scene had not been complete without it. In the throng were races from all over Norrath, and they were all monstrously powerful. There were wood elves and high elves, half elves like him. Even the dreaded Iksar were there. Uhrlik felt a stab of fear as he felt the affinity that his other form had developed with the Iksar. Had he allied himself with the evil lizards? Had he seen the forbidden city of Cabilis with his own eyes?<br>
<br>
The army marched into the dark city and the doors slammed shut with a laugh that could only come from Innoruuk himself. It was filled with the embodiment of Hate. The sound like grinding bones etched itself into his memory forever. <br>
<br>
Somewhere through the night he had warmed up. He felt as if he wasn’t alone anymore. Shooting bolt upright and throwing off a blanket that hadn’t been there before, the young warrior faced a confusing scene. There was a campfire lit and rabbit was cooking on a spit over it. There was a young high elf woman sitting on the other side of the fire. She was attractive, but there was a hardness in her eyes that spoke of great pain and the desire for revenge. There was also something about her that spoke of class and distinction. Had she been a noble's daughter perhaps?<br>
<br>
The young woman looked up from the rabbit to check on him. She licked her fingers and smiled at him when she saw he was awake. “Good, I was starting to worry about you. That must have been a terrible sight to have caused you so much pain.” She saw the confusion writ strongly on his face and chuckled, “My name is Annastrianna Starflower. I am a paladin of Tunare. I found you alone and freezing out here, and something compelled me to stop. I can only imagine the Mother directed my feet this night.”<br>
<br>
“But I don’t believe in Tunare.” Uhrlik whispered absently.<br>
<br>
“Doesn’t matter. I do, and I believe she led me to you. So now I have to help you.” Annastrianna sighed. “There isn’t much I can do for you aside from the fire, food and blanket. I have an axe that I don’t use anymore, and you are welcome to it. Your strength is obviously greater than mine is so perhaps you can get better use of it than I did.”<br>
<br>
“I am grateful for any help you offer.” Uhrlik looked at the woman suspiciously. He found it hard to believe that anyone would help him without an ulterior motive. Sometimes he felt like the last soul with a shred of honor or nobility in all of Norrath.<br>
<br>
They ate in almost unbroken silence. Both stared into the fire with the same lost look on their faces. It turned out that Anna (As Uhrlik soon abbreviated her name to and much to her chagrin) had seen more of Norrath than he had. She had seen the massive continent of Antonica, while Uhrlik had never left Faydwer. He had only briefly visited the other races here. The warrior had seen the subterranean cities of Kaladim, home of the dwarves, and Ak’Anon, home of the gnomes. His time in Felwithe was short, though. They were far too puritanical for his liking. Casting sidelong glances at him when they thought he wasn’t looking. <br>
<br>
She told him stories of the Oasis of Marr and the deserts of Ro beyond the human city of Freeport. Tales of sand giants roaming the desert sands, massive tarantulas that instilled fear in the hearts of the desert beasts. She told him of men having lost their minds in the desert and wandering the sands until their death. They believed that everything was a mirage and lashed out. “The only humane thing to do,” She told him with a heavy heart, “Is to put them out of their misery.”<br>
<br>
After the fire had burned low, Uhrlik relayed his story to his new friend. “So now I am on a mission to avenge my father…and mother.”<br>
<br>
Anna nodded slowly, “The harbingers of Hate have taken much from me as well. But that is a story for another time. We should sleep now, I need to be on my way early tomorrow.”<br>
<br>
Uhrlik’s mind worked furiously that night, and sleep came in fits and spurts. Was that what his mother had seen? Was he fighting Innoruuk or was he going home to meet him?  The questions burned in his mind. Could he trust Annastrianna? He felt as if he could, but he wasn’t sure anymore.<br>
<br>
The morning came quickly and Anna was nearly ready to leave. She had donned her heavy bronze armor and was packing the rest of her gear. “Oh, before I forget,” she said as she began digging through her pack. “Take this.” The young paladin handed him an axe with a minotaur emblazoned on the shaft. It was a good weapon, with a fair balance and weight. It proved to be superior to his short sword after a few practice slashes. He thanked her heartily and thought about that blade biting into an orc, or better, Dvinn himself.<br>
<br>
“I believe we will meet again,” she started and smiled. “The Mother does not create such encounters without a plan. When you are ready to take your revenge, I will be there.” Annastrianna laughed, “Perhaps we will get strong enough to knock down the gates of Hate itself one day.” She continued laughing as she started off through the woods towards Butcher block Mountains.<br>
<br>
Uhrlik froze dead in his tracks at her statement. He began to breathe again once he could no longer hear her chuckling in the distance. He shook himself back to the moment and started off to the north for another day of scouting Crushbone castle.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
The Story of Uhrlik<br>
Part Seven:<br>
Diversions gone awry<br>
<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Uhrlik spent days scouting the castle. He spent every waking moment trying to formulate a plan to get in and exact his revenge. Pushing the hate down, the young warrior tried to focus his thoughts but could not. Something was very wrong.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Ducking behind a wall, Uhrlik stopped and listened inward. What he heard froze him in his tracks. Resounding in his head was the lullaby that his mother had sung to him as a child. It was the melody that had calmed his restless spirit and quieted his turbulent soul. A wave of peace washed over him, as strong and insistent as the hate that burrowed in his blood. The two clashed within him, vying for control over the destiny of the young man. His concentration shattered, the warrior ran from the domain of the orcs.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp His emotions raged between seething hatred and composed tranquility. There seemed to be no controlling it, no end to their struggle for his heart. Suddenly, Uhrlik heard a sound. A yell for help! One of the younger hunters must have ventured out too far.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Uhrlik dashed out of the tunnel to find a young female ranger racing for the guards with three orc centurions hot on her tail. He unsheathed his axe and raced after them, shouting insults at them to make them turn. As each one did, the axe bit into them and one by one, the orcs all fell to his blade.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The young woman was very grateful, and thanked him endlessly between heaving gasps for air. As the warrior escorted the wounded girl back to the guards he felt something disturbing. The warring in his head had stopped for the moment. <br>
<br>
He had always been inclined to help people in need, even at the expense of his own safety, even at the risk of his own death. This natural sense of nobility had forced him to take action, but it was the killing of the orcs that had sated his hatred. The effect was only momentary, he found as the factions began tearing his consciousness apart again. The only way to calm his mind was to kill, but he could not bring himself to do it without honor, for the good of the Feir’Dal. Regardless of his nobility and honor though, there was still a dark part of his soul, darker even than the hate that crawled in his mind, where a new bloodlust was born.<br>
<br>
Uhrlik knew that this new confusion rending his mind would shatter any hope of getting his revenge if he could not learn to control it. He also knew that there was no way that he could focus on controlling it if he was still in the Faydark. He had to leave the forest, perhaps even leave Faydwer itself. He took a lesson from Annastrianna and began the trek to Butcher Block Mountains to take the boat over the Ocean of Tears to Freeport and the massive continent of Antonica. Maybe somewhere in the endless lands he could learn to control his mind, or at least forget himself in mindless slaughter.<br>
<br>
The boat creaked as it tumbled over the rolling whitecaps. Its masts groaned as their sails strained in the sobbing winds. Uhrlik had heard a tale that the Ocean of Tears had earned its name from a woman that lost her one true love in a vicious sea war. The woman, once she learned of his death, stole a ship and sailed into the sea he had died on and cried for a hundred years. She cried and cried until she, too, died. The story got somewhat muddled here, since no one was sure whether the crying came from her restless spirit haunting the ocean, or if the gods had heard her sobbing and instilled the very water with it to serve as a reminder of the horrors of war. Either way, the ocean had a saddening presence. The very air was oppressive. The warrior was glad to see the stone towers of Freeport coming into view.<br>
<br>
Freeport. The city his father had been born in. He never saw it again after that fateful mission. Breathing the salt air mixed with the horrid smell of the slums nearly made Uhrlik vomit. He was grateful to disembark from the boat and get his land legs back. The whole trip made him ill.<br>
<br>
He found that the guards here were no better than anywhere else when it came to half elves. They tolerated his presence, no more. He could see their shifting eyes and greedy smiles. They fingered cudgels and swords with roguish unwashed hands. These guards reeked with corruption. The Teir’Dal had a hand in this, he was sure.<br>
<br>
Regardless of the sinister guards, Uhrlik wandered the city. He listened to stories of underwater goblin cities in a far-flung corner of the continent. There were stories of fetid spiders raiding halfling lands with sadistic glee. Sometimes, it was said, if you killed one of the carrion spiders, you would find the remains of halflings. The stories ranged from the disgusting to the bizarre, but the youth listened to them all. Some he could tell immediately were complete fabrications, like the one about an ancient civil war. Humans wielding so much magical power that they created a bottomless pit that was rumored to lead to the God of Mischief’s domain. He laughed when he heard that one, but the drunkard telling the tale glared at him.<br>
<br>
Still chuckling, Uhrlik wandered some more through the streets, occasionally popping into a shop to see the wares being offered. As he wandered, he heard a man’s voice shouting and laughing.<br>
<br>
“Amlik! Amlik, is that you? Where have you been…?” The man’s question died as Uhrlik turned to face the source. A finely dressed knight, in full polished plate armor stopped a few feet from him. “I apologize, I thought you were someone else.” The knight’s tone turned sour as he turned to walk away.<br>
<br>
“How did you know Amlik?” Uhrlik asked the knight.<br>
<br>
“It has been many years since I mentored the man. I took him under my wing, once.” The man’s cold eyes warmed slightly and drew a distant cast. “My name is Sir Lucan D’Lere. I am Captain of the guards here in Freeport. Did you know Amlik, young one?”<br>
<br>
“I met the man once.” The warrior replied coldly.<br>
<br>
“On Faydwer, I presume?” Lucan eyed up the youth and dismissed the questions that were obviously burning in his mind. “No matter. I don’t suppose I need to tell you to keep your neck out of trouble here? If you aren’t careful in Freeport you might find your neck in a noose or worse.”  D’Lere’s face turned to a frigid scowl as he warned the young one. He could see the contempt in Uhrlik’s eyes, surely.<br>
<br>
It boggled Uhrlik’s mind as Lucan stalked away from him and he went on his way again. A knight that had given up everything he believed in for a scrap of power that barely extended beyond the point of his sword. His kind of authority, if it could be called that, never lasted. Tyrants like him were always put down like a rabid animal. It was said that the road to civilization was paved with the bodies of tyrants. Unfortunately, it was more frequently paved with the bodies of a tyrant’s victims first. Still, someone would come along and slay this Sir Lucan D’Lere, of that Uhrlik was sure.<br>
<br>
Wandering some more, the young one found a gate to the city. He meandered through the stone portal and the sand beyond and was glad to feel the grass under his feet. His back still itched from where the guards had been staring. They were most likely sizing him up, trying to find the best place to plant their swords.<br>
<br>
Uhrlik closed his eyes and recalled the tale that Annastrianna had told him of the oasis beyond this city. Step by step, he followed the story. He followed through the wasteland of North Ro, and at last finding the salty ocean that met the sand, he turned and followed the coast where he eventually found himself in the Oasis of Marr.<br>
<br>
There it was. The youth lumbered up the nearest dune and took in the sights of the oasis. The crocodiles that Anna had told him about crawled from the sea and roamed freely on the land. There were massive beetles and undead roaming unchecked through the sands. He could feel the hatred in those cold, lifeless eyes as they searched the sand for some respite. <br>
<br>
The hatred within pulsed in his head like a drum at the sight of the fleshless bones. One turned to face him as if Uhrlik was the embodiment of all of its torment. It cackled wildly as it charged him. Its eyes were burning maniacally as flame erupted from its hands. The skin on his arms began to smoke and smolder. Blisters opened on his cheeks as he hefted his weapons.<br>
<br>
The young warrior charged the thing with a roar of pure rage. He hacked at it with his axe and his practice sword, but found the animated bones to be far more agile than he had anticipated. It dodged and parried as it punched him with sun-hardened fists. It threw its arms wide every few seconds and new blisters and burns appeared on Uhrlik’s skin. With every punch he could feel his energy waning.<br>
<br>
As he slashed, it dodged, and the youth kicked the bleached bones with all of his might. The skeleton’s teeth ground in its hatred and it prepared to burn him again, but Uhrlik persisted in his onslaught. His axe blade caught the thing in its collarbone. Pieces of bone flew in all directions as Uhrlik used the momentum of the first swing to continue into a second. The blade bit into the long empty skull with a crunch and the bones collapsed in a heap of chips.<br>
<br>
Slowly the wounded warrior lowered himself into the sand and began to tend to his wounds. There was a salve that he had learned to apply to his bandages to cool the blisters and stop the bleeding. He was bruised and burned, but he was alive. <br>
<br>
Soon he found friends that helped him combat the dangers of the Oasis. There was a new rage in his head now, along with a new peace to war against it. His nights were spent restless at best. Nightmares haunted him with visions of the door to Innoruuk’s domain, the dark lord’s spiteful laughter echoed in his skull. This sight he had learned to expect, but now there were new visions, new horrors.<br>
<br>
He saw Crushbone castle, dilapidated and rotting. He was on the ground with Dvinn standing over him laughing. The sinister Dark Elf twirled the black bladed dagger in his right hand as he held something up in his left. No matter how many times he tried to focus on the glowing amorphous thing in the Ambassador’s left hand, the more it writhed into instability. The rage and Hate bubbled up in him so strongly that he could never see more than a few moments of that vision before they woke him up with a white knuckled snarl.<br>
<br>
The most recent vision scared him more than anything had ever scared him in his life. In the vision there was a set of eyes looking up at him. They held great wisdom, and they looked at him with adoration, complete devotion. Their shade was a blue so bright and alive that he could see his own soul in them. Every time he dreamed of them his mother’s song reverberated in every fiber of his being. Those eyes held the promise of hope, drowning his hatred and quenching his raging bloodlust. The whole of earthly emotion bowed to the love in those eyes as it echoed that in his own shadowed heart. The impossibility of this dream always made him wake weeping in the sand.<br>
<br>
The oasis was filled with cutthroat gangs and wandering ghouls, the insane men that Anna had told him about. The undead littered the desert almost as much as the breed of orcs that thrived in this hostile region. The Deathfist orcs, a rusty green rather than the sickly blue of their cousins on Faydwer, traveled a beaten sand road between two of their numerous camps so constantly that it was termed “the orc highway”. They wandered the desert preying on the weak and wounded, they grouped together with more ferocity and efficiency than their smaller cousins did. Even the cutthroat gangs traded with them and admitted some of the more clever of the breed into the gangs.<br>
<br>
Uhrlik and his friends had just finished clearing a camp of cutthroats when one of the friends mentioned a familiar name. “Annastrianna? You know her?” he asked the bronze-clad paladin as he removed the blade of a jagged sword he had recently purchased from the back of a female ogre. <br>
<br>
“Aye,” he replied. “She mentioned you to me as well. She told me to come find you and tell you that she will be waiting for you at the Estate of Unrest on Faydwer.”<br>
<br>
The young one thought for a moment. “I will have to seek her out soon,” he took out a cloth and wiped the blade clean before sheathing it. “But I am not ready to seek my revenge yet. I am not strong enough yet, and I do not possess enough control.” The last he admitted grudgingly.<br>
<br>
As the last of his words left his mouth, the group was suddenly beset by two of the wandering ghouls. They howled and shrieked in their strange language as they slashed at the group with their fetid claws. They were strong, and the situation was dire, but the group acted quickly and set themselves in their positions. Uhrlik laughed and swore at the ghouls, causing them to forget about the rogue that quietly slipped behind them. The cleric began to cast a spell to force the restless spirits back into their graves.<br>
<br>
The paladin, Baldaranian, hacked away at the ghouls while Uhrlik’s blades flashed through their rubbery flesh. The rogue, a massive barbarian that they had picked up along the way, smiled as he punched his harpoon into the back of one ghoul. He chuckled with glee as he watched it drop. The other ghoul turned and began rending the barbarian with a sickening fervor.<br>
<br>
After one slash the rogue’s arm began to turn a pale yellow and he started foaming at the mouth. The ghoul attacked him relentlessly and the cleric fell to the ground exhausted moments before the sly barbarian fell lifeless to the ground. The ghoul turned on the cleric next, but Uhrlik stepped in the way. He forced the thing to vent its fury on him instead. He could not allow another member of his raiding party to die by this abomination.<br>
<br>
He could see it was starting to weaken, but he was unexpectedly left alone to fight it. Baldaranian shouted to him from several paces away, “Run! There’s a sand giant coming this way. You’ll never finish the ghoul in time to escape it!”<br>
<br>
Uhrlik could not escape though, and he knew it. He would have to fight on so that his friends could get to safety. He forced Baldaranian to run regardless of him and fought on. He was getting weak, but the ghoul was nearly finished. Then the head of the giant came into view.<br>
<br>
The giant sneered down at Uhrlik with cracked, yellowing teeth. He had an unwashed face and a dirty whitish cap upon his head. He laughed and charged after the young fighter. <br>
<br>
The ghoul fell limp to the ground as Uhrlik finished it and he ran as fast as he could, already weakened and bloody. The giant caught up quickly and bashed him with a mighty fist. The breath rushed out of Uhrlik’s lungs and he gasped desperately for air as he continued to run. He dodged over the dunes with the giant on his heels. Abruptly the adolescent fighter tumbled down a dune and fell unconscious under the sand.<br>
<br>
When he awoke, there was a rusty green orc standing over him. His heart leaped into his chest and he tried to scurry away. The orc merely cocked his head to the side and extended a hand.<br>
<br>
Reluctantly, Uhrlik took the orcs hand, raising slowly to his feet. He found that he had been bandaged while he was insensate. A groan escaped him uncontrollably as he stood uneasily.<br>
<br>
“Few run from Giants and live,” the orc spoke fluently, not like the halting orc speech one could expect from a normal orc, as if they had learned the common tongue only recently. “I am Ortallius. I am not like other orcs. Rathmana saved me from the Dervish Cutthroats as a baby. Now I serve the Temple of Solusek Ro. I believe I can help you.”<br>
<br>
“How can you help me? I mean, other than what you have done for me already.” He clumsily fingered the wrappings over his wounds.<br>
<br>
“My emotions flare wildly because I am an orc. I once had to learn control over them, as you need to learn it now. Your nobility and honor is not enough. The hate and rage will destroy you.” Ortallius stated sadly.<br>
<br>
“Will you teach me?” Uhrlik asked hopefully.<br>
<br>
Ortallius nodded silently for a moment, then looked down at the young one and said, “It will not be easy, it never is. But I believe you can do it. Even if you hold no godly allegiance.” The last the orc mumbled apprehensively.<br>
<br>
So Uhrlik began to learn from Ortallius. The orc taught him to identify the feelings behind his actions. “This will unite you within.” He frowned, showing a great pain inside, one he reserved for himself alone.  “But it will not make you whole. I cannot teach you anything to fill that void, as I have never filled my own.” <br>
<br>
Some days later, the young warrior was ready to seek out Annastrianna at the Estate of Unrest. He had learned all that he could from the reformed orc. He found the rage that the Hate had given birth to danced with the peace of his mother’s Calm. Like some twisted opera they played on inside his head, and he – the poor player on the stage – choreographed his movements to their symphony.<br>
<br>
Soon, the Oasis was behind him as he made his way back to his home, made his way toward his revenge.<br>
