<br>
The Story of Uhrlik<br>
Part Eight:<br>
The Rebirth of Hate<br>
<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The sand gave way to grass, which in turn gave way to the sand again as Uhrlik strode through the gates of Freeport once more. He hoped that the wait for the boat would not be long. Just as he had the first time coming through the town, the youth was soon hopelessly lost. <br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “Hey boy,” A familiar voice laughed. “I figured out why you remind me so much of Amlik.”<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp His stomach turned to ice as Uhrlik turned to face Sir Lucan again, “Oh?” He asked dispassionately. “Do tell.”<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “You’re his son, aren’t you?” The look on Uhrlik’s face must have given him away, as Lucan continued. “Ha! I knew it! And you’re a half elf to boot. I wonder what Elven bitch your father ravished to sire you!” The once paladin doubled over in laughter.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The rage burst out of control. “You know nothing of my mother.” The hate writhed in his veins as Lucan merely laughed harder. He was holding his side now he guffawed so hard. “Apparently you know nothing of my father, either.”<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Lucan stopped laughing instantly, “And what do you mean by that, little half breed?” Growing more and more angry, he stalked after the boy as Uhrlik backed away from him. “I taught your father everything he knew. I was the one that got him that last assignment before his regiment disappeared. The Indigo Brotherhood has sent word all the way to the Kunark outpost to watch for any of them, and to kill them on sight.”<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Uhrlik shook his head and continued to back away. “You still don’t get it, do you? Amlik Shadowblade got married to a wood elf, my mother. He became a legend to the Feir’Dal. He did everything he could to stop the Teir’Dal invasion of Faydwer.”<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “So where is this legend now?” Lucan hissed.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “He’s dead.” Uhrlik gnashed his teeth. “He died because of you for teaching him. He died because you volunteered him to be a sacrificial lamb.” Lucan looked dumbstruck. “That’s right, the bones of his men litter the Crushbone encampment. He was the only one to survive that encounter, and the Dark Elf he brought there organized the orcs for the sole purpose of killing my father. So now I hold you responsible for my father’s death.”<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “And what do you propose to do about it, boy?”<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “Nothing… yet.” The young warrior glared threateningly.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “I don’t suppose your legendary father told you about his other missions in the service of Innoruuk, did he?” Lucan was obviously shaken by the news of Amlik’s death, and perhaps a bit remorseful for his involvement in it. He was hurt by Uhrlik’s words, now he had to hurt him back. “Did he tell you about the mission where he posed as a guard of Qeynos to corrupt the guards there? A mission that went very well, I might add. I bet he didn’t tell you about the high elven bitch that he took as a mistress there. Or about the child that was born of their union.” Lucan straightened when he saw the shock on Uhrlik’s face. He was satisfied with the results, casting a shadow on the perfect father’s memory. “No. I didn’t think so. He refused to care for the child, and the woman would have been outcast for having a half elf child, so she left it, I believe, on the steps of a Tunarean temple.” Lucan sighed whimsically, confident in crushing this child’s heart. “I wonder what ever happened to the boy.”<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “I see you’re exerting your true power again, Lucan.” A voice called out dubiously from behind Uhrlik. “Picking on children, I see.” Another knight stood firmly with his sword bared, its point in the dirt. He was also dressed in polished plate armor but wearing a different livery on his tunic. There was something about this knight that was different from the shifty eyed, slimy guards that infested the rest of Freeport, and he obviously did not like Sir Lucan D’Lere.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “This is none of your concern, Valeron. The boy and I have some business to tend to.”<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The man shook his head and the patch over one war-lost eye gave the action even more gravity. “You will leave the boy alone. You may control the rest of Freeport with that disease you call a militia, but we control this part. You will leave North Freeport now or you will leave here in pieces.” Valeron lifted his sword and stood ready.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Lucan snarled and backed away, sheathing his own sword. “We will meet again, boy.” Turning on his heels he walked away with his back straight and his head high.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Uhrlik bowed deeply to the knight, “Thank you. I am not sure that I would have survived that encounter. My name is Uhrlik Pureblade.”<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The knight did not take his eyes from Lucan’s back until he was well out of sight. “I am Valeron Dushire and what I did, I did not do for you.” Valeron glanced at the boy and sighed, seeing the confusion on his face. He took on a lecturing tone and continued. “I lead the Knights of Truth, the Order that monster has forsaken for the promise of a scrap of power. He corrupts our children and tarnishes the name of Freeport.”<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “So why don’t you just kill him?”<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The knight eyed Uhrlik askance with a look that said he had thought of it before, “The ways of our Order are not discussed so openly, especially not with one such as you. Now, please go in peace.”<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “One such as me?”<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “Yes,” Valeron growled. “One that owes no holy allegiance, one that is not from our Order, or any Order for that matter. You are a drifter, a ruffian in the eyes of the Knights of Truth. We allow your presence here, and we will protect you should you deserve it, but we will not dispense our secrets to a thug and mercenary. Now good day, child. May the Lightbringer illuminate your way.”<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Uhrlik took the dismissal for what it was and wandered back through the city, ever watchful for Lucan around every corner. He stopped occasionally for directions to the port, but few people deigned to stop for him. Those that did thought him a beggar and refused to answer any questions. He eventually found the port and the boat was just arriving. The youth noted that even though he may seem like a drifter and a mercenary, he was far more than that. He was a boy with a dark destiny, and while his heart was not as pure as his steel, he would always try to live up to his mother’s nobility and his father’s honor.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp There was a new hate breeding in his heart now. It mingled with the hatred for Dvinn. Uhrlik wondered whether killing Dvinn, the tool of his parent’s demise, would be enough to satisfy the hatred that seized his heart. The crying of the ocean offered no opinions.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
