The Story of Uhrlik<br>
Part Nine:<br>
Counseling Caution<br>
<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Far to the south of Kaladim, buried in the Butcher Block Mountains, lay the entrance to Dagnor’s Cauldron. A mangled landscape bereft of life, the Cauldron was littered with jagged peaks and towering stone spires. The sun never shone here, and it rained almost constantly. An explosion of immense magnitude created the Cauldron, but the origins of the explosion escaped history. Its origins are not without their own fairy tales, however.<br>
<br>
There was one such tale that told of a great war against the Kedge, an ancient aquatic race that was thought to have disappeared from the world eons ago. It was said that the Kedge city extended the entire length of a pristine lake, its golden towers shimmering in the sunlight where they rose majestically out of the water. The Kedge were fiercely isolationist people, resenting any invasion of their lands and waters, including the estate of the dwarven noble built high on a hill overlooking the lake. <br>
<br>
The origin of the war against the Kedge is unclear, but it was generally believed that they attacked the noble’s estate, and the noble brought his political and military power to bear. The noble, the story went, brought a wizard of unsurpassed skill to put an end to the bloody war. The wizard, whose name also eluded the ages, brought down a hail of fire followed by a stone from space that was the size of an island. The rock slammed into the golden city, evaporating most of it and burying the rest. One small portion of the city survived the ordeal, underneath the newly created mountains. The surviving Kedge thrived here in their blessed isolation, their church of Prexus intact, for ages until recently rediscovered by some of the boldest adventurers.<br>
<br>
The detonation was so powerful that it completely upset the balance of the gods in the region, and one of the most foul deities reached down and snatched the lives of the inhabitants of the noble’s estate. Their minds were twisted to the point that they forgot what life had been like, feeling nothing but the torment of undeath and the desire to share that torment for a moment’s relief. Even the animals were changed into foul, aggressive beasts bent on the destruction of all living beings that invaded their domain.<br>
<br>
The god made its curse more horrid by cloaking the entire estate in eternal night. The undead roamed the grounds freely, trapped in their pain, but unable to step foot from the estate. This was exactly the kind of place that Uhrlik expected to find Annastrianna.<br>
<br>
Upon entering the tunnel, Uhrlik found several people crouching against the stone walls. There was a cleric of Tunare passing through the group healing as she went. Her eyes were sunken and heavy with exhaustion, but she continued with her duty. Uhrlik stopped and dug his bandages out of his pack and began binding the worst of the wounds until the cleric could regain enough strength to cure them further.<br>
<br>
“Be careful if you’re going in there,” a young wood elf druidess warned him. “Those creatures swarm.”<br>
<br>
“Aye,” a female half elf agreed gravely. She had been bandaging herself and several of her compatriots, but turned her attention to him briefly. “They attack in groups, as if they’re social in some way. And there always seems to be more of them, like they aren’t allowed to stay dead.” She shuddered uncontrollably then. Uhrlik noted that the bronze armor that this woman wore very nearly matched his own, and the giant two-handed sword at her side marked her as a warrior like himself. He chuckled slightly to himself that they looked like two Great Oranges of War.<br>
<br>
“I thank you for the advice.” He bowed slightly. “I’m looking for someone, she said she would meet me at this accursed place. Perhaps you know of Annastrianna?”<br>
<br>
The druidess and the warrior woman both nodded and exchanged glances. “And you are?” The druidess asked.<br>
<br>
“My name is…”<br>
<br>
“Wait. You’re Uhrlik, right? The druidess smiled. “I hunted with you in the Crushbone encampment.”<br>
<br>
“Amarante?” Uhrlik squinted and stepped slowly towards the girl.<br>
<br>
“Yes.” She laughed, “And the grump over there is Dauphine.” The warrior woman looked incredulous but the young nature walker went on, “It’s been a long time. I trust you’ve been well?”<br>
<br>
“It’s been hard without someone there to keep me out of trouble,” The young warrior winked and continued, “Where is Anna?”<br>
<br>
“Anna? Oh you mean Annastrianna. She’s still inside. I believe she’s at the fountains. Head straight in, follow the tunnel and you can’t miss the fountains.”<br>
<br>
“I thank you.” Uhrlik bowed. “It was good to see you again, Amarante, and it was nice to meet you Dauphine.”<br>
<br>
The warrior dashed down the long tunnel until it opened into a spacious estate. The grounds hinted at having once been well tended, with lush greenery and precisely cut paving stones. The fountains sat along the path that eventually led to the manor, slick and stagnant water festering in their pools. There were two cultured labyrinths dominating the sides of the walkway, their once carefully tailored leaves now sprouting cruelly barbed thorns. <br>
<br>
While he waited at the fountains, Uhrlik listened to the sounds of unrest. The shrieks of pain, the howling of eternal torment rending the stale air. The cacophony of affliction blended together like a tragic opera. Great people had been driven from this estate screaming, gripping to the last shreds of their sanity. Others had been made fully mad. Unrest was hardly the place to be if you were unsure of yourself or your skills, and those skills it forged in the fire of relentless combat.<br>
<br>
At long last, Annastrianna walked down the path from the manor with a smile on her face. She wore an old and well-used breastplate that looked quite sturdy despite its dusty appearance. The sword in her hand glowed slightly as if it defied the darkness of the accursed place.<br>
<br>
“I knew you’d get here sooner or later.” Anna chuckled. “You’re nearly ready to seek your revenge, aren’t you?”<br>
<br>
Uhrlik nodded, “I have learned a modicum of control, and I must put the hate to rest. Or at least, I must put that hate to rest.” He added, thinking of Lucan.<br>
<br>
“As I said before, when you are ready to go I will be there. Just ask.” She saluted him briefly and turned to face a howling ghoul creeping down the path towards them. “Shall we?”<br>
<br>
“Indeed.” The young warrior smiled, “I have to hone my senses as much as my skills, and what better place than this?” Weapons bared, he joined Annastrianna in slaughtering the denizens of Unrest.<br>
<br>
For weeks, Uhrlik fought against the undead tide. He joined forces with Amarante and Dauphine constantly, and other hunters as they came. Frequently they were overwhelmed, rushing for the tunnel for the safety of the open air. Uhrlik escaped bloodied and broken because it was not in him to turn and run. He could not allow any that hunted with him to come to harm while he had an ounce of energy left in him.<br>
<br>
The legends proved true about nothing that had lived on the estate had gone uncorrupted except for one thing: Death Beetles. Uhrlik could not figure out the relationship between the place and the beetles. Had the beetles been there before the war? Were these beetles just twisted representations of what they had been, like the rest of the estate? Were they drawn here because of all the rotting, fetid corpses? Were they like the Crushbone slavers? Did they serve as slave drivers, tormenting the souls of those imprisoned here, or were they nothing more than giant parasites feeding on the ample supply of dead and dying flesh? Whatever the case, they were as twisted and swarmed as aggressively as the corpses themselves. <br>
<br>
One day, Uhrlik was hunting with Amarante and Dauphine, and they met up with Annastrianna inside the manor. The mansion was worn and decaying, its furniture was ransacked and cobwebbed, though the warrior had never seen a spider here.<br>
<br>
They had just slain the last of the skeletons in what had been a large ballroom, its chandelier still hanging over the harlequin floor tiles. The fires still burned in one of the dead dancer’s eye sockets as the four turned their attention to the stairs at one end of the room.<br>
<br>
Annastrianna looked them over and said, “You three stay here, I’m going to look for something upstairs.” They nodded and she dashed up the right staircase.<br>
<br>
Moments later, Anna rushed back into the room, leaping over the small railing on the stairs, “Stand ready! I do not know what just attacked me, but I can feel my skin burning from within.”<br>
<br>
A skeleton rushed down the stairs with rigid inefficiency, straight for Anna. It bashed her as the two warriors joined the fray. Soon after, a black clad gnome strode down the stairs. He was pale and sickly looking, but there was an aura of power about him. He sneered as he looked over the group, “You three I might have forgiven for interrupting my studies, but this paladin,” he said with acid on his tongue as he eyed Anna, “must be destroyed. I cannot stand your type. So mighty, so righteous you make me sick.”<br>
<br>
“Who are you?” Amarante asked as she healed Anna again. She was growing weary, and it was showing.<br>
<br>
“My name is Khrix Fritchoff, and I’m conducting very important work here.” The gnome saw Amarante healing Anna and his face turned even more sour. “I see. If that’s the way you want it…”<br>
<br>
His attack was quick, a burst of flame around his hands and Amarante dropped to the ground. Her veins started turning blue as a poison raged under her skin. “Get her out of here!” Uhrlik shouted at Dauphine, who swiftly snatched the young druid over her shoulder and ran for the tunnel.<br>
<br>
Anna slashed the skeleton once again and it shattered into pieces. The gnome turned his attention on her as he had been eyeing Uhrlik after Amarante was evacuated. His fists turned into a blur as he punched the two mercilessly. They did their best to parry the blows, but the gnome was far stronger than he appeared.<br>
<br>
“You interest me, Warrior.” The little man stated as he focused his assault on Annastrianna. “I can feel an immense hatred brewing in you. It’s the thing that motivates your every action, the rage behind every kill. You try to convince yourself that you’re doing Norrath a service, that you’re being as righteous as this one,” he spat at Anna. “But in your heart you know the truth.”<br>
<br>
