The Story of Uhrlik<br>
Part ten:<br>
The Blood of Innocence<br>
<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The necromancer’s words still troubled him. There seemed to be no way of getting his revenge without becoming a monster on some level. Like the riddles his father told him when he was a child, this seemed to be a question without an answer.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “You look troubled, Uhrlik.” Anna whispered. Amarante still slept, but it was hardly a sound sleep. “Do not let the words of that crazed gnome get to you…”<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Uhrlik cut her off, “He’s right and we both know it.” Thoughts rushed through his head and his emotions were flaring. The rage and the song clashed together like oceans at war. “I have to go. I need to be alone.”<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “You’re going to do it now, aren’t you?” Dauphine asked. “You’re going to seek your revenge in this state?” She shook her head. “I do not think that is wise.”<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The young warrior stood up and started down the tunnel towards Dagnor’s Cauldron, “Never let it be said that I was wise.”<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “May Tunare guide you this day, friend.” Anna bowed and sat down to meditate.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Dauphine still shook her head at the haste of his decision. Finally she harrumphed and said, “Fight well, we shall meet again.”<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “Tell Amarante goodbye for me.” Uhrlik bowed and ran from the tunnel.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Loping over the blasted landscape, the warrior tried to block out all thought, all emotion. He needed to focus in this hour of his revenge. By the time he reached the pass to the Butcher Block Mountains only the Rage and the Song remained. <br>
<br>
By the time he reached the orc hill in Greater Faydark, his mind was like the blades he clutched in his fists, hardened steel and razor sharp. The little pawns and centurions sent to guard the hill cowered as he ran by them. They knew that they could not stop him and wisely stepped aside. <br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp In the Crushbone encampment, the orcs shivered as he ran by them. Only the legionnaires rushed him, shouting, “Your deeds are an affront to all I believe.” Or, “I shall rid the land of another infamous villain. You are no match for a legionnaire.” He had to smile at that.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp At last the castle stood before him. It no longer seemed as ominous as it was once. There was a group of hunters preparing for an assault on the castle throne room, and seeing him rush the door, they followed quickly behind.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The guards at the door died swiftly. They tried to run, but the warrior would not allow any to escape his vengeance. The group followed him into the throne room and immediately set to destroying the legionnaires within.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “Time to die, Uhrlik.” A guttural orcish voice grunted.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The warrior turned just in time to parry the axe of the infamous Lord Darish, Emperor Crush’s younger brother. There was a bloodlust in Darish’s eyes as he lunged forward, pressing his attack. <br>
<br>
Uhrlik returned the attack and swiftly brought the orc on the defensive. Within moments, Uhrlik slashed through the orc’s defenses and his jagged sword blade sliced his foe open, mortally wounding him. Darish sank to the ground, whimpering as he died.<br>
<br>
Looking around, the warrior saw that the younger hunters had done well in taking the throne room. It was empty except for the last oracle, which they were engaging now. Again he smiled, the new hunters were getting bolder. The Crushbone empire would never extend into the Faydark while hunters such as these lived there.<br>
<br>
Uhrlik peered behind the throne and started up the steps to Crush’s tower. That would be Dvinn’s hiding place, he was sure of it. The rage was growing loud in his head as it thundered through his veins. He could feel his vengeance close at hand.<br>
<br>
In the tower, the Emperor was nowhere to be seen, but there was his quarry. The Ambassador stood looking out the window at the dig site across from the moat. He twirled the strange black bladed dagger in his right hand as he scratched his chin unconsciously with his left.<br>
<br>
The warrior crept up behind the Dark Elf as if to take him by surprise. Dvinn’s ear twitched suddenly, and he whirled around with amazing speed. The dagger thrust out with precision, just missing Uhrlik’s chest.<br>
<br>
“I remember you.” Dvinn laughed. “You’re that pathetic shadowknight’s son. It’s been a long time. How is your mother?” He sneered as if he already knew the answer.<br>
<br>
“She is dead and you are going to pay.” Uhrlik stated blandly as their blades met again and again.<br>
<br>
“And you’re going to be the one to kill me? Where others, much greater in strength than you I might add, could not. I highly doubt it.” The sneaky Teir’Dal ducked behind Uhrlik and kicked him with all of his might, sending the warrior out the tower window.<br>
<br>
Uhrlik crashed hard on the hard ground, flat on his back. He tried to get up but was horribly out of breath. He watched as Dvinn leaped from the window and stood over him, straddling him. Dvinn laughed mercilessly at the fallen warrior, and his laugh was like slime coating slime. It was a viscous, oily laugh that made him want to retch listening to it. <br>
<br>
He could not believe that his path had come to this. His planning and contemplation, all to die by the hand that had killed his parents. It made him want to weep as he saw the dagger rising above his chest. He had failed his parents, failed everyone that had ever died in this monster’s path. How many had he killed? How many innocents had fallen along this man’s way? And here he lay, breathless and weak, unable to do anything about it.<br>
<br>
“I’ve found something!” An elven slave shouted from the dig site.<br>
<br>
Dvinn shot a look over to the slaver nearest him. “Check it out, you fool!” The demented rogue nearly salivated with anticipation.<br>
<br>
“You have found nothing, slave.” The orc spat.<br>
<br>
“Then kill him.” Dvinn shouted. “I will not have this operation compromised because the slaves won’t accept what they are. Make an example of him.”<br>
<br>
It was all Uhrlik needed to gather his strength back. His breath came back and he heaved his heavily armored foot up into Dvinn’s back. Something crunched as his foot hit squarely in the man’s ribs. Dvinn staggered forward and Uhrlik stood up with his blades ready. He thought of all the people the man had killed before. Of all the people…<br>
<br>
From the corner of his eye, Uhrlik saw the other slaves raising their mining picks and squaring off against the slaver. He didn’t like his odds anymore.<br>
<br>
Dvinn stood before him, dagger at the ready. “Why don’t you just lay down and die? I promise I’ll make it quick for you. Not painless,” he laughed, “but quick.”<br>
<br>
“I can’t let you harm anyone else.” The youth dashed forward slashing at the sinister Ambassador. “You see, I’ve finally figured out the answer to the riddle.” His mother’s song reverberated in his ears so loudly that he thought that the world must be hearing it now as well, but the rage was nowhere to be found.<br>
<br>
“What riddle, boy?” Dvinn attacked the warrior again, kicking and bashing where his slick, poisoned dagger could not penetrate.<br>
<br>
Uhrlik slashed the Ambassador’s long coat open across the chest, revealing the dark blue skin beneath. A long red line opened on the man’s chest, and he began to bleed like a crimson waterfall. “I could not get revenge on you without becoming a monster myself.”<br>
<br>
“Indeed.” The monster sneered. “So then you’ve accepted your fate? You will become a monster to destroy me?”<br>
<br>
The two circled around each other, panting with exhaustion. They were both bleeding in a dozen places or more. They were bruised and breathless from the intense fighting, but they held their weapons with skill and readiness. Both were determined that this would be a fight to the death.<br>
<br>
Just then, a bluish aura surrounded Uhrlik. His wounds began to close and he felt revitalized. As they circled, Uhrlik saw a human, slightly older than himself with a patch over one eye. The man wore a symbol of Tunare around his neck and was casting his healing on the wounded warrior.<br>
<br>
“I have paid for your death with the blood of innocence, but I will not be what you are. I was blind to not see it before. You have killed too many people, and for that you must pay. This is not about revenge anymore.” He slashed furiously into the elf’s defenses, meeting with a waning resistance.<br>
<br>
“Then what is this, whelp?”<br>
<br>
“This is Justice.” Uhrlik made a final thrust with his sword, punching through the other man’s coat, the jagged blade running straight through Dvinn’s black heart.<br>
<br>
There, the Ambassador that had slaughtered countless people in search of an ancient artifact, the assassin that had enslaved an empire and murdered the dreams of a young boy, there Dvinn died.<br>
<br>
Uhrlik bowed to the cleric that had just saved him. “I thank you. You were just in time, I think.”<br>
<br>
“I heard the calling of the Mother. She told me to tell you that even though you have forsaken her, she has not forsaken you. My name is Brenidil Gentlehands, and I have some friends I think you should meet…”<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
