<br>
So he boarded the Maiden’s Voyage, that vast ship with its calico sails billowing in the wind like gossamer butterfly wings. The ship sailed through the dragon-infested waters known as Timorous Deep. Waters that he had swum once, but that was a story all to itself. The warrior was going home again, back to Kelethin.<br>
<br>
The ship cut through the water with a lazy grace. It lolled through the waves with amazing speed, but made painfully slow turns. Such a massive craft could not turn with any speed, but it certainly tried to. All aboard kept a watchful eye, waiting for any sign of the fish-dragon Faydedar. It was not entirely unknown for him to attack the boat and devour the passengers. This trip went uneventfully, and Uhrlik sighed in relief when he boarded the shuttles to take him the rest of the way to the docks in the Butcher Block Mountains. <br>
<br>
When at last he caught up with Kinluianae, the young druidess was tending wounds at the orc lift underneath Kelethin in Greater Faydark. She appeared haggard, but somehow wiser than he had left her. She seemed to have been exhausting her energies so that others could continue the fight for orc hill. That was always her way, though. She was selfless in the face of combat.<br>
<br>
