<br>
“We need to talk about what I saw at that party last week. You know what I’m talking about.”<br>
<br>
Indeed he did. <br>
<br>
It was a loud party, with alcohol flowing freely. His guild mates were all around him, as was his sister. Kin, as he called her, loved parties. She danced away from his side to the music of a bard and joined with the shuffling throng. <br>
<br>
Uhrlik watched her dance for a while, to make sure she was safe. Something was not right inside him. He felt nervous without a reason, and his stomach felt as if it were a pit of ice. His mother’s song blared in his head, growing louder and louder. <br>
<br>
“She dances well for one so young.” A woman’s sultry voice said from his side.<br>
<br>
Uhrlik turned to face the dream that had haunted his nightmares since he first heard the Song. The blue eyes so bright and alive that he could see his own soul in them stared into his so intently that he began to squirm unconsciously.<br>
<br>
“She’s my… uh…sister, sort of.” He mumbled to her.<br>
<br>
The woman nodded, “I thought as much.” Her head cocked to the side slightly. “You remember me, don’t you?”<br>
<br>
“You’re Lamila, the leader of Feir’Dal, my home and sanctuary.” Uhrlik answered in a rush.<br>
<br>
“But you stare at me as if you’ve never seen me before. Did I suddenly grow a third eye that everyone is too polite to tell me about?”<br>
<br>
The warrior gasped and tried to laugh at the same time and his words came out in a spluttering cough, “No, no. I’ve… never been… this close to you.”<br>
<br>
She laughed, “So then I’m either hideous or I smell bad.”<br>
<br>
“No, just the opposite. You are the most beautiful woman I have ever laid eyes on.” He realized what he had said and he blushed profusely. He scanned the crowd to find some way out of the mess his tongue was making, but found only Kin staring at him intently and smiling widely.<br>
<br>
Lamila blushed, “Why thank you. I suppose you’re attractive underneath that silly helmet.” The druidess began removing his helmet and he backed away swiftly when her fingers grazed his cheek. The simple touch sent shocks through his entire body. <br>
<br>
Uhrlik shook himself back to the moment, “Sorry, what were you saying, Kin?”<br>
<br>
Kin threw her hands up in the air, “Ugh. Mother, give me strength.” She chuckled at him and continued, “I was saying you love her. I know it and you know it. I’d be surprised if she doesn’t know it. I’m sure she loves you, too.”<br>
<br>
The warrior blushed again, “You really think so?”<br>
<br>
“Yes, now stop blushing whenever I mention her. You’re a warrior for crying out loud. Aren’t you supposed to be a rough and tumble type?”<br>
<br>
“Sorry, I will try.”<br>
<br>
“You should know that I have been talking to her as well. Acting like your ambassador in a way.”<br>
<br>
“You haven’t?” Uhrlik shouted in terror.<br>
<br>
“Yes, I have.” She smiled mischievously. “She blushes every time I mention you to her. I suppose that’s a good sign. Either she loves you or she gets sick whenever she thinks of you.” Kinluianae laughed heartily at Uhrlik’s wide-eyed gape. “I’m kidding, really.”<br>
<br>
