He sent Lamila a cryptic message stating that he “needed to talk to her about something”, and waited for her while hunting the elusive crazed goblins in the Butcher Block Mountains. Kalysha and another member of Feir’Dal hunted with him that night, but only Kalysha knew what was about to happen. <br>
<br>
Lamila finally tracked him down and sat patiently nearby while the three dispatched a final goblin. Uhrlik then drew up all of his might, all of his inner strength and stood before the woman he loved. He kneeled in front of her, looking into those crystal blue eyes that made him weak in the knees. He could see that she was nervous as well, as she laid a hand on her stomach to calm the butterflies within.<br>
<br>
If I don’t do this now, Uhrlik thought to himself, I’ll kick myself forever. He took a deep breath. Better do it now before we both lose our nerve. He handed her his gift in two small bags and spoke without a hint of the uncertainty that rolled in the pit of his stomach. The Hate and the Song were nowhere to be found, as if they both waited with bated breath for what was about to come. “Lamila,” he started, “I love you, and all I can offer you is forever. Will you marry me?”<br>
<br>
Tears streamed down Lamila’s face as she opened the bags to find one dozen Firiona Roses. “Yes, I will marry you, Uhrlik. Thank you for the dozen roses, I love them and you always.”<br>
<br>
“Thank you for forever,” he smiled widely. For the first time, he understood what his father had found in his mother. He understood the wave of peace that this kind of love could bring, the kind of love that his hatred could not stand against.<br>
<br>
Lamila laughed, her nerves finally settling, “So do you want to tell the family or should I?” <br>
<br>
Uhrlik saw more of Norrath than he had ever imagined in the coming months. He never left Lamila's side as she went about her guild duties. He loved to watch her work. Occasionally, it would all be too much and she would turn to him and bury her face in his chest, crying that she couldn’t do it anymore. He would hold her and stroke her hair and whisper a few words in her ear and she would stop crying and beam a smile at him, hugging him tightly.<br>
<br>
Lamila had motivated him as well. Uhrlik spent every moment of his sleepless nights hunting. Lamila was far more experienced than he was, and he desired nothing more than to rise up and be as near to her equal as he could. He would hunt with his guild mates when they were around, but more often than not he hunted alone.<br>
<br>
All too soon the date was set. The guests were invited, the food was being made and the alcohol was being brewed. Uhrlik’s stomach was uncharacteristically aflutter. He knew that they had planned this down to the smallest detail, but he felt as if something was missing. There was something he had to do.<br>
<br>
So one night, while staying at an inn in the Common lands, Uhrlik crept from the bed and left Lamila resting comfortably on his pillow. He left her a note telling her that he had one last errand before they could be married. He ran through the Commons to the Desert of Ro, at last finding what he was after.<br>
<br>
A small tent with a lone figure squatting under it, staring thoughtfully out at the stars. Ortallius looked as pained as ever. Uhrlik approached him and greeted the orc with a bow.<br>
<br>
“I had to see you again,” the warrior started. “To tell you that I have filled the void that once marred my heart.”<br>
<br>
Ortallius merely stared at him quizzically. “Do go on, Uhrlik.”<br>
<br>
“I have found a family with The Feir’Dal, but most importantly, I have found love. She has filled my dreams as long as I can remember, and my heart as long as I have known her. She was the part of me that was missing, cast on the winds of fate at my birth. Now I have found her, now forever begins.”<br>
<br>
The gentle orc smiled at the last, “At last you have peace. Good luck to you, brother.”<br>
<br>
The two shook hands one last time. As Uhrlik turned away, he saw the glimmer of a tear rolling down Ortallius’s face. Perhaps he would know peace someday, it wasn’t likely, but the warrior hoped with all his heart.<br>
<br>
The day of the wedding arrived, the sun just rising as Uhrlik crept into the room to slip back beneath the covers. Lamila woke just as he got his boots off and asked, “You’re up awfully early. Dressed too? I thought I’d have to drag you out of bed kicking and screaming.” She paused and mumbled, “As usual.”<br>
<br>
“Very funny. Will you be joining me today or will I be getting married alone?”<br>
<br>
Lamila chuckled at him and rushed to get dressed. Since he was dressed already, Uhrlik sat in a chair near the door and watched her. She was so beautiful. There was a rosy tint in her cheeks and she glowed in anticipation. He could not help but stare at this vision as she transformed herself into the regal wonder that she presented to the rest of the world. A truth much closer than most would know, Lamila was always very tight-lipped about her past.<br>
<br>
The warrior found himself blinking profusely to clear away the tears welling in his eyes. He had found his happiness, and he knew that she felt the same way.<br>
<br>
“What are you staring at?” Lamila asked and he shook himself back into the moment. She was dressed and ready to go now. She stared at him with an odd look on her face, but it seemed that she couldn’t stop smiling.<br>
<br>
“My future.” Uhrlik answered simply.<br>
<br>
She turned her back to him and said in a broken voice, “If you’ve settled up with the innkeeper already, we’ll be heading out now.”<br>
<br>
Uhrlik nodded as she began weaving her energies. She knew that he had settled their bill already, but it was an excuse for him to not see her cry.<br>
<br>
A portal of energy enveloped him and they swiftly found themselves in the Butcher Block Mountains. They ran west, to the ocean. The spot of their wedding was near the ocean, just south of the fishing village there.<br>
<br>
Guests had already begun arriving, and they milled about introducing each other when they found someone new. Annastrianna was there with her new little friend Bruska, the dwarven cleric. Amarante and Dauphine arrived, and most of Feir’Dal was running from all over Norrath to witness this event.<br>
<br>
Galanea, Lamila’s younger sister, sat with her back resting against a knotted old tree. Uhrlik sat next to her so Lamila could have the last few moments before the wedding to herself. Her nerves were a wreck, and there were still guests to greet and makeup to fix and prayers to be made. His last words to her before he left were “Calm, breathe.”<br>
<br>
“Are you nervous?” Galanea asked wryly.<br>
<br>
Uhrlik shook his head, “I won’t be nervous until it actually starts.”<br>
<br>
“You are a strange little man,” the druidess laughed.<br>
<br>
“I suppose I am.” He said thoughtfully. “You know that Feladin, my brother and best man, won’t be able to make it today?”<br>
<br>
“Really? Why?” Lamila’s sister asked in shock.<br>
<br>
“He is stuck somewhere on Kunark and can’t get here in time.”<br>
<br>
“That’s sad.” Galanea sighed.<br>
<br>
Uhrlik shrugged, “It’s ok really. Lamila’s maid of honor is my ‘little sister’ Kin, won’t be here either. She’s been missing on Kunark for a week or two now.”<br>
<br>
“I’m sorry to hear that. I’m sure she’s all right.” Her comforting words held a tone that said she didn’t believe them herself. Uhrlik merely nodded and grunted in response.<br>
<br>
A throng of women surrounded Lamila as she made her final preparations. They encircled her so completely that she was utterly obscured. Uhrlik couldn’t help but laugh as they all fussed over her. He had a constant line of men shaking his hand and saluting him. Two of them, a reformed Teir’Dal necromancer named Obien, and a stout little dwarf named Rabby, even gave him a cookie. Bright eyed and capable Kitanion rushed up to him and gave him a high five and patted him on the back. All three were members of his guild, and it warmed the warrior deeply to see so many of his family there.<br>
<br>
A black robed High Elf strolled confidently into the mix and stopped before Uhrlik. He smiled widely and hugged him. “Congratulations, Uhrlik. I have a present for you.” The man reached into a fold in his robe that hadn’t been there a moment before and extracted two wedding rings, diamonds set in the odd velium metal.<br>
<br>
“Thank you for coming, Valley. I’m honored that you came.” He bowed to yet another member of his extended family.<br>
<br>
Suddenly, there were three quick claps of thunder followed by a single bolt of lightning. The line streaked from the cloudless sky and struck the ground where the ceremony was about to take place. A woman stepped from the bolt as it disappeared harmlessly. She was a half elf in appearance, but it was clear that she was not normal. She was a member of a strange race of demigods that sought tirelessly to right the wrongs that the gods committed upon their creations. They led a weary life, as their limited powers often left them unable to help, leaving them as nothing more than observers and witnesses to the crimes of the Pantheon.<br>
<br>
She spoke in tones of rolling thunder, “My name is Aughisky.” The milling crowd stood silent as she continued. “I hope you don’t mind that I invited some of my friends.”<br>
<br>
Uhrlik stood wide eyed, “Of course not, the more the merrier.”<br>
<br>
In a geyser of flame two more of the Outsiders appeared. They introduced themselves as Kreena and Hawthorne and stepped off to the side, speaking in a language that he could not understand.<br>
<br>
“An impressive gathering,” Aughisky smiled. “Are we ready to start?”<br>
<br>
Uhrlik nodded, “Aye, now more than ever.”<br>
<br>
“Would you like to face the sea or your guests?” She asked him as if she already knew the answer.<br>
<br>
“We would like to face our guests.”<br>
<br>
“Do you have the rings?”<br>
<br>
Uhrlik nodded again and handed her the rings that Valley had just presented him.<br>
<br>
“Good. I will bless them and return them at the appropriate time. You have written your own vows, have you not?”<br>
<br>
The warrior laughed, “Yes we have.”<br>
<br>
The women began to depart to take their places next to their dates, and Uhrlik saw his bride. His heart skipped a beat as she strode nervously to his side. Every emotion he had ever felt paled next to their love as it mixed in his heart. There was nothing else in the world but this woman, nothing but the path that they would take as one from now on. Finally, he could understand the vision that had haunted him his whole life. This feeling was the whole of earthly emotion. This is what mattered.<br>
<br>
Aughisky cleared her throat and waved a hand over the assembly. People sat silent as her hand passed over them. When she came back to Lamila and Uhrlik, their backs to the crashing surf below them, she began to speak. Her voice was loud enough for the host of guests to hear, yet she did not yell or strain. Her tone reminded the warrior of a spring rain, soothing and nurturing. “'Let the four directions be honored that power and radiance might enter this rite for the good of all beings.<br>
<br>
“'We stand upon this sacred Earth and in the Face of Heaven to witness the Rite of Marriage between Lamila and Uhrlik of the clan Feir'Dal. <br>
<br>
“Just as we come together as family and friends so we ask for the greater powers to be present here within our circle. May this sacred union be filled with their presence.”<br>
<br>
A lush green energy poured from the woman’s hands, “With the blessing of the deep and fruitful earth, we call upon the powers of the North!”<br>
<br>
The green was replaced swiftly with a blazing inferno, “'With the blessing of the inner fire of the sun, we call upon the powers of the South!”<br>
<br>
A fluid blue seeped from her hands and quenched the fire, “With the blessing of the sacred waters of the pool, we call upon the powers of the West!”<br>
<br>
Her hands flashed with a white wind, “With the blessing of the clear pure air, we call upon the powers of the East!”<br>
<br>
All four of the magical energies combined into one flow that surrounded and permeated the couple before settling into the ground around their feet, “May the harmony of this circle be complete....Blessed Be.<br>
<br>
“As the Sun and the Moon bring light to the earth do you Uhrlik and you Lamila vow to bring the light of love and joy to the union and do you vow to maintain these vows in freedom, for as long as they shall last?”<br>
<br>
The two spoke in unison with complete conviction, “I do.”<br>
<br>
Aughisky nodded to herself and smiled, “Then at this time profess your vow one to the other.” She motioned to Lamila.<br>
<br>
“Uhrlik Before you came into my life my heart was lost and alone. Now with you by my side I am truly whole. You are my Champion my Future and my reason for Being.” She sniffed and her eyes welled up with tears, “Today I give you my heart body and soul, I will Love you till forever fades and beyond.” The tears streamed down her cheeks unhindered. She was not afraid of them, rather, they were a symbol of her love and its purity.<br>
<br>
There were tears flowing freely among the guests, and another flash of crystal blue water marked the entrance of another of Aughisky’s race. Uhrlik took a deep breath and tried to calm his jittering nerves. All eyes were on him now, and he began his vows while mustering all of his vaunted courage.<br>
<br>
“Lamila, Heart of my heart, I knew from the first time I lay eyes on you that there could be no other. In you I see my future. You are my motivation and my motive, the reason for my every breath. I am here today to pledge myself to you in words as I have in mind, body and soul. I will love you until forever fades and mountains crumble to dust…Then I will love you still.”<br>
<br>
A small cheer rose among some of the more rowdy guests, and Aughisky and her fellows glared at the interruption. The demigoddess addressed them again when the guests were quiet once more, “All things in Nature are circular, these things are part of the Great Mysteries. Lamila and Uhrlik, you have given me rings to bless as your symbols of these Great Mysteries of Life.” A small glow emanated from her hands as she handed Uhrlik his ring for Lamila.<br>
<br>
“Please repeat after me. ‘Lamila, I give you this ring as a symbol of my love for you. Let it remind you always as it circles your finger, of my eternal love. You are my beloved and I marry you today with this ring as I give you my heart, my body, and the very breath of my soul.’”<br>
<br>
Uhrlik repeated the words, remarkably keeping his voice from cracking.<br>
<br>
She turned then to Lamila and handed her the ring to give to Uhrlik. “Lamila, please repeat after me. ‘Uhrlik, I give you this ring as a symbol of my love for you. Let it remind you always as it circles your finger, of my eternal love. You are my beloved and I marry you today with this ring as I give you my heart, my body, and the very breath of my soul.’”<br>
<br>
Lamila intoned the words, her face more serious than Uhrlik had ever seen it.<br>
<br>
Another cheer rose from the crowd and none made a move to stop them. When they were finished, Aughisky continued, “Let those assembled here bear witness that Lamila and Uhrlik of the clan Feir'Dal are joined in love. May their love partake of the beauty, majesty and power of the sacred land. May they grow together in wisdom, joy, and harmony. My own blessings and the blessings of all those assembled be with you.”<br>
<br>
Their ogre friends Bhah and Klutzee led the resounding cheer. The party that followed the ceremony was filled with cake and liquor. Lamila and Uhrlik handed out what Aughisky’s friends had given them, and they personally thanked everyone for coming. The four demigods disappeared sometime during the celebration, waving goodbye to all and good luck to the couple.<br>
<br>
Annastrianna approached her old friend, “How does it feel being married?”<br>
<br>
Uhrlik stopped and thought for a moment, “Right. It just feels right.”<br>
<br>
Hours flew by and the party dwindled slowly. There was still much liquor left unconsumed when it was over. At the end it was as it had started, just Lamila and Uhrlik. They held each other and Uhrlik sighed in contentment as the peace washed over him. It had been a good day.<br>
<br>
And so, Lamila Earthmyst and Uhrlik Pureblade became married in name as they had already in mind, body and soul. They began their life together as Lamila and Uhrlik Mystblade, a life they lead still with as much love and conviction as they started with.<br>
