The Story of Uhrlik:<br>
Oath of Steel<br>
<br>
<br>
        As every historian of Norrath knows, there can be no peace without war. There is no golden age that does not end in blood. There are no miracles without tragedy. Such was the case with Uhrlik’s heart. Aye, he was married, and happily so. But there was still a dark place in his heart, a blackness in his veins that terrified those nearest him.<br>
<br>
        As the song of his love for Lamila grew stronger, so too grew the Hate that roiled in his blood. The rage devoured conscious thought when he fought. His teeth gnashed and he snarled in fury with every mighty slash of his weapons.<br>
<br>
He stood over the last of the felled drachnids, the foul creations of Mayong Mistmoore that littered the Dread Lands, with a monstrous presence. The thing’s slick green blood coated the warrior’s arms to his elbows, with splatter marks marring his breastplate. He clutched his drenched blades tightly and his eyes shifted to find his next kill. Something caught his ear and he turned to listen to his friends talking.<br>
<br>
“What did you say?” He asked, rather insistently.<br>
<br>
Feladin, his near-brother, guild mate and paladin of Tunare, jumped as if startled. “I was saying that Thunderhart and I came from Freeport. We spoke with the Knights of Truth and we’ve been charged with getting a confession from a fallen knight.” Feladin stood of a height with Uhrlik, though somewhat thinner. He was a compassionate soul that had saved Uhrlik’s life on numerous occasions with a well placed heal or the coveted gift of life that lay in his hands. That occurred even before they found out they were brothers.<br>
<br>
“We’ve also been told to eliminate him.” Thunderhart smiled dangerously. A dwarven paladin of Brell, Thunderhart had a bearing about him that made one forget that he was significantly shorter and more stout than he seemed. He was an honorable soldier, and he held nothing but contempt for those that had given up their holy station for the promise of quick power.<br>
<br>
Uhrlik’s eyes narrowed, “Lucan.” The paladins nodded. “I have a score to settle with him. We should go now.”<br>
<br>
“Are you going like that?” Lamila chuckled. The rage subsided at the sound of her voice and Uhrlik smiled at her. He laughed at himself as he saw the mess that the spider-things had made of his armor. He took out a dry cotton cloth and began wiping down his weapons and armor.<br>
<br>
“I have spoken with some of my close friends, as I know Feladin has also. They will be arriving on the border of West Freeport shortly.” Thunderhart explained. “The time is now, he must face justice.” There was a sound in his voice that spoke of long buried pain suddenly crying out from his core.<br>
<br>
Tucking the cloth away when he had finished Uhrlik stood and nodded to Lamila. His reddish breastplate gleamed and his weapons nearly glowed in his anticipation. “Let’s go.”<br>
<br>
Lamila began weaving a portal and they found themselves standing at the druid rings in the Common Lands. The rings were an amazing sight, despite their dilapidated appearance. They were wide stone circles that focused the natural energies of Norrath, enabling the druids to magically transport their small hunting parties or themselves to a given location. Each ring had its own feel, almost like its own taste. Some rings were beyond a young druid’s use, the flavor hidden from them until they were deemed ready.<br>
<br>
The construction of the rings had been lost to antiquity, only marginally recreated when the wizards began building their monstrous spires. Much more technological than spiritual, the spires were created as symbols of mortal triumph over Nature and the Pantheon. They required knowledge instead of faith, and so only the most learned of wizards could operate them.<br>
<br>
The four ran across the Common Lands until they reached the very borders of West Freeport. The stone walls that led to the city gates ending with the clean lines and right angles that the humans seemed so fond of. They were pockmarked and weathered by a constant sand filled wind, the land between here and the city gates had been completely eroded and blasted since the town was built.<br>
<br>
Leaning on the wall was Lamila’s younger brother, Webberran. A lithe ranger, he wore a wry smile as if he hinted at some secret that only he knew. With him were two familiar faces, the Ogres Bhah and Klutzee. Bhah was a Shadow Knight, like Uhrlik’s father, and his mate (Uhrlik assumed) Klutzee was a Shaman. Both were extremely well traveled and had no love whatsoever for the arrogant knight or his corrupt minions. They had no love for the Knights of Truth either, but that was beyond the point.<br>
<br>
So they began assembling the forces. Another friend slithered into the group as they prepared for the battle. He was a tall, well-muscled Iksar Monk named Mephiska, and he sneered at them, baring his sharp fangs. This smile seemed disconcerting to anyone that was unfamiliar with the Iksar race. They hated everything that was not Iksar, and they were not afraid to admit it. Meph, as they called him, had ventured long and far from Cabilis, the home of the lizard people of Cazic Thule, and so he had become somewhat used to the outsiders’ presence. He didn’t necessarily like outsiders, but he acknowledged their usefulness.<br>
<br>
“Ah, Thunderhart. My good friend,” Mephiska hissed. “This seems an adequate force.”<br>
<br>
The time grew short, and several more companions joined them. As well as Mephiska, another druid and a cleric, both friends of Thunderhart’s, came to them. A bard came to the call of Feladin, as had the two Ogres and Webberran. <br>
<br>
As they prepared, the energies of the druids and the cleric and the shaman infused Uhrlik’s body. He felt stronger, faster and sturdier than he had before. His nerves were steel and his mind was razor sharp. He had been waiting for this fight for a long time. The fallen knight would pay, not for his words to a young boy, not for the truth he had shared. He would pay for the torment he had inflicted on a young boy and the doubt he had cast on the memory of a father.<br>
<br>
Feladin wore an uncharacteristically grim visage. To him this was a problem that had to be dealt with. It was a duty and an obligation sent to him by Tunare, one that he would follow absolutely, but he didn’t have to like it. He had his own quarrels with Lucan but the man’s execution was a very serious matter. Uhrlik’s near brother refused to take this matter lightly.<br>
<br>
Thunderhart wore an equally severe countenance. He sat cross-legged on the ground idly stroking his beard and staring at – or through – the symbol of Brell Serilis that graced the face of his shield. There was a feel about him that this was the calm before the storm. Perhaps he debated the morality of the slaughter to come. Judging from the man’s unwavering honor, Uhrlik doubted that this was the case.<br>
<br>
The warrior and Mephiska waited somewhat impatiently as the others meditated before the fight. His parents had never managed to get Uhrlik to sit still long enough to get any use of the skill. As his parents had suspected, magical energies burned in his veins, but he had turned his back on those powers long ago. Slaughter was what he was made for, to square off against an opponent and win or die.<br>
<br>
A pair of hands, Lamila’s hands, cupped his face as she stared in his eyes with concern. It was then that Uhrlik realized that he gripped the hilts of his weapons so tightly that he was quivering. He took a deep breath and relaxed. The perpetual knot in his shoulders loosened slightly. Glancing around, he found that the others were ready. <br>
<br>
Mephiska and the two Ogres appeared to be relishing in the mindless death to come. Webberran replaced his smirk with a thoughtful, far away look. The paladins wore the same sober facade that Uhrlik knew that he wore himself. Lamila chewed on her bottom lip the way she always did when she was worried about him.<br>
<br>
The time had come. The plan was that Feladin would coax the errant knight out of the protection of the barracks and into the open. As the paladin strode across the biting sand towards the West Gate, the others assembled near the grassy border of the Common Lands. Any attempt to slay Lucan in the open would be madness, his corrupt guards were everywhere and would jump to his aid without thought. Long moments passed and there was nothing but an eerie silence. <br>
<br>
“He’s been gone too long.” Lamila stated nervously. “I’m going to see if he’s all right.” She ran into the city and disappeared behind the stone walls.<br>
<br>
Moments later, Feladin and Lamila came into sight, running at top speed to outdistance the flood of Militiamen at their heels. Lucan was there, too, leading the charge like the first drop of water in a tidal wave.<br>
<br>
Suddenly, Lamila stopped and began summoning her energies. A hole in space opened briefly and she and Feladin were gone. The guards began to walk back into the city, muttering dejectedly and slaying the snakes and bats that swarmed in the expanse back to the city gates.<br>
<br>
A few guards found the Ogres and the Iksar and rushed them. They obviously thought that the three would be no problem since they did not call their corrupted brethren back. That was not the fight that interested Uhrlik, though.<br>
<br>
Standing before him was an object of his enmity. The man that had cast a shadow on his already blackened childhood. The fallen knight eyed him warily, seeing that the son of Amlik was no longer a simple child.<br>
<br>
“You know that this has to end,” Uhrlik stated.<br>
<br>
Lucan nodded, “It’s time to put one of our memories to rest.” He shook his head dismissing any conditioned retorts, “I heard you killed Dvinn. Your father worked very hard to put that man in power.”<br>
<br>
Uhrlik cut the man off, “And died for the effort. We both know the story.”<br>
<br>
“Too bad that you left Crushbone when you did. They found what they were looking for after all.”<br>
<br>
“Which was?”<br>
<br>
Lucan shrugged arrogantly, “Whatever it is, it’s on its way to the Dark Lord Innoruuk now.”<br>
<br>
“Doesn’t matter. I’m here to dispense justice…”<br>
<br>
“Justice?” The fallen knight interrupted, “This is revenge, boy, plain and simple. Don’t try to play the Judge, you are a Dark Avenger, a monster as vile as Dvinn and I ever were.” Steel flashed into Lucan’s hands as he drew his sword. “Now either kill me or join me in the Dark Lord’s service, but don’t patronize me.”<br>
<br>
The Hate roiled in Uhrlik’s veins with such force that he thought he might see his skin boiling. “I will not stop until the last of you is destroyed.”<br>
<br>
The erstwhile paladin’s mouth twisted in disgust, “Why don’t I just kill you now and save you the trouble? Martyr you now instead of making you beg for death from Innoruuk?”<br>
<br>
“For that you’d have to kill all of us as well, foul deserter.” Feladin spat. “We’ve come for your confession.”<br>
<br>
“And your head.” Thunderhart added.<br>
<br>
Feladin quirked an eye at the stout paladin and turned his attention back to Lucan. “Repent now and your end will be merciful.”<br>
<br>
Uhrlik turned his head to find all of his friends with weapons bared and severe faces. The bodies of the foolish Militiamen littered the ground beyond them. Then all hell broke loose.<br>
<br>
Mephiska leaped over Lucan and landed lightly, turning his momentum into a spinning kick that sent the knight reeling into the two paladins. Uhrlik rushed in to engage Lucan as Feladin and Thunderhart hacked away at his defenses. Lamila summoned her energies and suddenly a black cloud of vicious insects surrounded Lucan, stinging him mercilessly. His skin flared and blistered, but the fallen knight never missed a step. His blade flashing in the waning sun darted from one attack to another, blocking all advances. Bhah and Uhrlik rushed in to close Lucan’s escape.<br>
<br>
Seconds dripped to minutes, but it became obvious that Lucan’s defense was waning as fast as the sunlight. He took on a hunted look and tried to back his way towards the city, looking for the First among his corrupted confidants, Brother Jentry. The cleric was not showing though. The fallen knight had been abandoned to his fate, it seemed.<br>
<br>
Spells flared and blades clashed, and all at once, Lucan’s sword dropped. Poison and disease ran rampant in his veins, the stinging insects jabbing away like a million tiny daggers. Fire and ice rained down on his head. Steel pierced his body from a dozen places. Sir Lucan D’Lere was dying.<br>
<br>
Suddenly, his skin began to turn to dust. His eyes and innards melted away leaving nothing more than a blackened skeleton. The corruption that had tainted the man’s soul had infested the man’s bones and given them unnatural life. He cackled maniacally and hefted his sword anew.<br>
<br>
The paladins and the cleric set themselves against the Animated Hate that was once a man. Chunks of bone flew apart from the remains as they hacked and blasted away and in short order, the thing screamed in rage as it finally released Lucan’s soul. The hate that had infected Lucan exploded out in a ring, and Uhrlik felt somehow dirtier for it.<br>
<br>
The last rays of sunlight faded and the group stood staring at the dust that had been a worthy foe. They left in ones and twos, but always in silence. They had executed a man that had once been noble and righteous, a man that could not see the way back, and it weighed heavily on them.<br>
<br>
There, Sir Lucan D’Lere, the man that had renounced his holy duty for the bloody hatred of Innoruuk, the man that had created the method of his destruction in Uhrlik, there, Lucan died.<br>
<br>
The next day, Feladin and Thunderhart appeared with their reward for accomplishing their task. Each held a greatsword blazing like the rising sun, a symbol of their faith and dedication. There was a peace in Thunderhart’s eyes, but Feladin’s carried a great sadness. It was unlikely that his near-brother would ever shake the feeling of that hate and the look in the eyes of a man that he had helped to execute. Uhrlik was not sure that he cared what the man had been, only that vengeance had been served…<br>
